05. The Poetry and Literature Center at the Library of Congress.]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|aw}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Billy Joe Shaver]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Americana Music Association|AMA Lifetime Achievement Award for Songwriting]]|years=2003}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Jack Clement|Cowboy Jack Clement]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Loretta Lynn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Americana Music Association|AMA Artist of the Year]]|years=2005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Neil Young]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{John Prine|state=expanded}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prine, John}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American bluegrass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American acoustic guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk guitarists]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Folk musicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mail carriers]]\n[[Category:Old Town School of Folk musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Maywood, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Paul Magnussen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Wrong word.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Prine"}
{"title_page": "George Stewart (American football)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach and former player}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox NFL biography|name=George Stewart|image=|image_size=|alt=|caption=|current_team=Los Angeles Chargers|position=Assistant Head Coach/ Special Teams Coordinator|birth_date=|birth_place=[[Little Rock, Arkansas ]]|death_date=|death_place=|high_school=|college=[[University of Arkansas Razorbacks|Arkansas ]]|undraftedyear= 1981|pastteams=[[Kansas City Chiefs]](1981)*|pastteamsnote=yes|pastcoaching=* [[University of Arkansas|Arkansas]] (1983)<br> Graduate Assistant \n* [[University of Minnesota|Minnesota]](1984-1985)<br> Offensive Line Coach\n* [[University of Notre Dame |Notre Dame]](1986-1988)<br> Linebackers Coach\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (1989-1991)<br> Special Teams Coach\n* [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (1992-1995)<br> Tight Ends/Special Teams Coach (1992-1994)<br>Special Teams Coach (1995)\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] (1996-2002)<br>Special Teams Coach(1996-1999)<br>Wide Receivers Coach (2000-2002)\n*[[Atlanta Falcons]] (2003-2006)<br> Wide Receivers Coach\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] (2007\u20132016)<br>Wide Receivers Coach\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers]] (2017-present)<br> Assistant Head Coach/Special Teams Coordinator}}\n\n'''George Stewart''' has been a coach in the [[National Football League]] since [[1989 NFL season|1989]] after spending a few years coaching in the [[College football|college]] ranks. He spent ten years coaching wide receivers for the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/08/07/george-stewart-minnesota-vikings-wr-whisperer/|title=George Stewart: Minnesota Vikings WR Whisperer|date=2013-08-07|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/george-stewart-minnesota-vikings-wr-whisperer-26204824-080713|title=George Stewart: Minnesota Vikings WR whisperer|last=Aug 8|first=foxsports|last2=ET|first2=2013 at 12:15a|date=2013-08-08|website=FOX Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> In 2017 he became the assistant head coach and special teams coordinator for the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chargers.com/team/coaches-roster/george-stewart?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Los Angeles Chargers|website=www.chargers.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/chargers/la-sp-chargers-lynn-stewart-20170521-story.html|title=Chargers special teams guru George Stewart made Anthony Lynn better as a player, so Lynn hired him as a coach|date=2017-05-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/want-to-make-the-chargers-final-roster-earn-this-mans-trust|title=Want to make the Chargers\u2019 final roster? Earn this man\u2019s trust|date=2019-08-28|website=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/sports/20170130/chargers-hire-george-stewart-as-special-teams-coordinator|title=Chargers hire George Stewart as special teams coordinator|date=2017-01-30|website=Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== NFL coaching ==\nHe began in [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] with the Steelers under [[Chuck Noll]] from ([[1989 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1989]]\u2013[[1991 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1991]]). He then went to [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay]] ([[1992 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1992]]-[[1995 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1995]]), where he coached tight ends. This was followed by a coaching stint in [[San Francisco 49ers|San Francisco]] ([[1996 San Francisco 49ers season|1996]]-[[1999 San Francisco 49ers season|1999]]). He was a wide receiver coach in San Francisco ([[2000 San Francisco 49ers season|2000]]-[[2002 San Francisco 49ers season|2002]]), four in [[Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta]] ([[2003 Atlanta Falcons season|2003]]-[[2006 Atlanta Falcons season|2006]]) and 10 seasons in [[Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota]] ([[2007 Minnesota Vikings season|2007]]-[[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|2016]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2018/3/21/17148522/terrell-owens-hall-of-fame-presenter-george-stewart-49ers-position-coach|title=Terrell Owens explains why George Stewart will present him at 2018 Hall of Fame ceremony|last=Fucillo|first=David|date=2018-03-21|website=Niners Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Stewart has been the [[Los Angeles Chargers|Chargers]]' special teams coordinator and assistant head coach under [[Anthony Lynn]] since [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|2017]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, George}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Little Rock, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings coaches]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football coaches]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons coaches]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers coaches]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers coaches]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Buccaneers coaches]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Razorbacks coaches]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Razorbacks football coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football coach and former player}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox NFL biography|name=George Stewart|image=|image_size=|alt=|caption=|current_team=Los Angeles Chargers|position=Assistant Head Coach/ Special Teams Coordinator|birth_date=|birth_place=[[Little Rock, Arkansas ]]|death_date=|death_place=|high_school=|college=[[University of Arkansas Razorbacks|Arkansas ]]|undraftedyear= 1981|pastteams=[[Kansas City Chiefs]](1981)*|pastteamsnote=yes|pastcoaching=* [[University of Arkansas|Arkansas]] (1983)<br> Graduate Assistant \n* [[University of Minnesota|Minnesota]](1984-1985)<br> Offensive Line Coach\n* [[University of Notre Dame |Notre Dame]](1986-1988)<br> Linebackers Coach\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (1989-1991)<br> Special Teams Coach\n* [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (1992-1995)<br> Tight Ends/Special Teams Coach (1992-1994)<br>Special Teams Coach (1995)\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] (1996-2002)<br>Special Teams Coach(1996-1999)<br>Wide Receivers Coach (2000-2002)\n*[[Atlanta Falcons]] (2003-2006)<br> Wide Receivers Coach\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] (2007\u20132016)<br>Wide Receivers Coach\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers]] (2017-present)<br> Assistant Head Coach/Special Teams Coordinator}}\n\n'''George Stewart''' has been a coach in the [[National Football League]] since [[1989 NFL season|1989]] after spending a few years coaching in the [[College football|college]] ranks. He spent ten years coaching wide receivers for the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/08/07/george-stewart-minnesota-vikings-wr-whisperer/|title=George Stewart: Minnesota Vikings WR Whisperer|date=2013-08-07|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/george-stewart-minnesota-vikings-wr-whisperer-26204824-080713|title=George Stewart: Minnesota Vikings WR whisperer|last=Aug 8|first=foxsports|last2=ET|first2=2013 at 12:15a|date=2013-08-08|website=FOX Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> In 2017 he became the assistant head coach and special teams coordinator for the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chargers.com/team/coaches-roster/george-stewart?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Los Angeles Chargers|website=www.chargers.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/chargers/la-sp-chargers-lynn-stewart-20170521-story.html|title=Chargers special teams guru George Stewart made Anthony Lynn better as a player, so Lynn hired him as a coach|date=2017-05-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/want-to-make-the-chargers-final-roster-earn-this-mans-trust|title=Want to make the Chargers\u2019 final roster? Earn this man\u2019s trust|date=2019-08-28|website=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/sports/20170130/chargers-hire-george-stewart-as-special-teams-coordinator|title=Chargers hire George Stewart as special teams coordinator|date=2017-01-30|website=Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== NFL coaching ==\nHe began in [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] with the Steelers under [[Chuck Noll]] from ([[1989 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1989]]\u2013[[1991 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1991]]). He then went to [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay]] ([[1992 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1992]]-[[1995 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1995]]), where he coached tight ends. This was followed by a coaching stint in [[San Francisco 49ers|San Francisco]] ([[1996 San Francisco 49ers season|1996]]-[[1999 San Francisco 49ers season|1999]]). He was a wide receiver coach in San Francisco ([[2000 San Francisco 49ers season|2000]]-[[2002 San Francisco 49ers season|2002]]), four in [[Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta]] ([[2003 Atlanta Falcons season|2003]]-[[2006 Atlanta Falcons season|2006]]) and 10 seasons in [[Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota]] ([[2007 Minnesota Vikings season|2007]]-[[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|2016]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2018/3/21/17148522/terrell-owens-hall-of-fame-presenter-george-stewart-49ers-position-coach|title=Terrell Owens explains why George Stewart will present him at 2018 Hall of Fame ceremony|last=Fucillo|first=David|date=2018-03-21|website=Niners Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Stewart has been the [[Los Angeles Chargers|Chargers]]' special teams coordinator and assistant head coach since [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|2017]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, George}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Little Rock, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings coaches]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football coaches]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons coaches]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers coaches]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers coaches]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Buccaneers coaches]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Razorbacks coaches]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Razorbacks football coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Bigmike2346", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Stewart_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Albania\u2013Greece relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Albania and the Hellenic Republic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Albanian-Greek|Albania|Greece|filetype=svg}}\n{{see also|List of ambassadors of Albania to Greece}}\n\n'''Albanian\u2013Greek relations''' are the [[bilateral relations|bilateral]] [[diplomacy|foreign relations]] between [[Albania]] and [[Greece]]. Due to the presence of [[Albanian communities in Greece#Immigrants|Albanian immigrants in Greece]] and the [[Greeks in Albania|Greek minority in Albania]], historical and cultural ties<ref>Kondis, Basil. \"The Greek minority in Albania.\" Balkan studies 36, no. 1 (1995): 83\u2013102.</ref> as well as the frequent high-level contacts between the governments of Albania and Greece, the two countries today maintain strong, yet at times complicated, diplomatic relations.\n\nBoth countries are members of many international organizations, including the [[Council of Europe]] and [[NATO]], and share common political views about the Balkans and the world, with Greece being a strong supporter of the [[Accession of Albania to the European Union|EU candidacy]] of Albania, by proposing \"Agenda 2014\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Agenda 2014 |url=http://www.mfa.gr/images/docs/periferiaki_politiki/agenda_2014_en.pdf |publisher=mfa.gr |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> for promoting the [[Enlargement of the European Union|integration]] of all the [[Western Balkan]] states into the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Greece's EU Presidency and the Challenge of Western Balkan Enlargement Policies in Light of the Crisis |url=http://www.suedosteuropa.uni-graz.at/sites/default/files/publications/Panagiotou%20-%20Greece%20EU%20Presidency%20West%20Balkans%20-%20CSEES%20WPS.pdf |publisher=suedosteuropa.uni |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Under the [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Greek EU Presidency]], Albania was granted official EU candidate status on 24 June 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=EU candidate status for Albania|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-439_en.htm|publisher=[[European Commission]]|date=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=201delEU>{{Cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/albania/press_corner/all_news/news/2014/20140624_01_en.htm |title=European Union \u2013 EEAS (European External Action Service) &#124; EU candidate status for Albania |date=24 June 2013|publisher=European Union Delegation to Albania}}</ref> which coincided with the 10th anniversary of \"Agenda 2014\" proposed by the Greek Government as part of the 2004 EU-Western Balkans Summit in Thessaloniki.\n\nGreece is Albania's largest foreign investor and main trading partner.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://balkaneu.com/greece-is-the-biggest-investor-in-albania/ | title=Greece is the biggest investor in Albania| date=25 June 2018}}</ref> Along with Italy, Greece has strongly supported Albanian Euro-Atlantic integration such as Albania's entry to NATO in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mfa.gr/en/blog/greece-bilateral-relations/albania/ |title = Greece's Bilateral Relations}}</ref> Cooperation between the two governments and business sector exists in numerous fields such as market, energy, military, tourism and culture, with large bi-lateral projects such as the [[Trans Adriatic Pipeline]] and hydroelectric power plants being implemented. Greece has also been Albania's largest donors as well as the leading donor of the [[National Theater of Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Greece gives 2.5 mil. Euro to Albania for National Theater|url=http://albanians.gr/25-ek-euro-dini-i-elladha-stin-albania-gia-ethniko-theatro.html|publisher=albanians.gr|date=17 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nModern diplomatic relations between the two countries were established in 1971 and today are regarded as positive.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/enlargement/albanian-official-we-are-much-more-pro-european-several-eu-members-302813|title=Albanian official: 'We are much more pro-European than several EU members'|work=EurActiv.com|date=16 June 2014}}</ref> Despite the two peoples sharing common traditions, culture, history, and inter-ethnic relations diplomatic tensions relating to the Greek communities in Albania and Albanian communities in Greece continue to play a role in how both countries and people view one another.<ref>Hart, Laurie Kain. \"Culture, civilization, and demarcation at the northwest borders of Greece.\" American Ethnologist 26, no. 1 (1999): 196\u2013220.</ref> Current issues in diplomatic ties of the two NATO states include the abolition of the status of war that remains in effect between Greece and Albania, due to the Greek-Italian war in 1940<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-calls-on-greece-to-abolish-war-declaration|title=Albania Asks Greece to Declare War Finally Over|date=18 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/war-peace-albanian-grek-relations/|title=\"War\" and \"Peace\" in the Albanian-Greek relations|first=Edison|last=Kurani|work=Independent Balkan News Agency|publisher=AM|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-calls-on-greece-to-end-state-of-war|title=Albania Asks Greece to End State of War|date=14 October 2013}}</ref> and the human right issues the Greek minority faces in Albania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/summaries/s.albania952.html|title=Albania: The Greek Minority|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/1400/albania/greeks.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115070035/http://www.minorityrights.org/1400/albania/greeks.html |archivedate=15 November 2014  }}</ref> Despite some obstacles, and contrary to media portrayal, Albanians and Greeks continue to maintain intertwined relations in their respective countries, with a growing push by academics, cultural groups, NGO's, ethnic minorities, mixed families and other non-state actors to forge closer and stronger social and political ties.<ref>https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00400327/document</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://journals.openedition.org/balkanologie/2221 |title = Lines in the Family. Aspects of Family-Related Migration in Greek-Albanian Border|journal = Balkanologie. Revue d'\u00c9tudes Pluridisciplinaires|issue = Vol. XII, n\u00b0 2|date = 31 December 2010|last1 = Mantzos|first1 = Costas|last2 = Peglidou|first2 = Athena}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-3-319-13719-3_7|chapter = Albanian Immigrants in the Greek City: Spatial 'Invisibility' and Identity Management as a Strategy of Adaptation|title = Migration in the Southern Balkans|pages = 123\u2013142|series = IMISCOE Research Series|year = 2015|last1 = Kokkali|first1 = Ifigeneia|isbn = 978-3-319-13718-6}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nBoth countries and peoples claim autochthonous status in their respective countries and the wider Balkan region which has led to shared kinship as well as contested claims throughout history.\n\nAs a result of the close proximity of the two countries and peoples, European genetic research has shown a degree of genetic similarity between Albanians and Greeks, as well as other southern European populations such as southern Italians and Cypriots.<ref>Sokal, Robert R., Neal L. Oden, Pierre Legendre, Marie-Josee Fortin, Junhyong Kim, Barbara A. Thomson, Alain Vaudor, Rosalind M. Harding, and Guido Barbujani. \"Genetics and language in European populations.\" The American Naturalist 135, no. 2 (1990): 157\u2013175.</ref>\n\nSince the nineteenth century, both countries have been separate nation-states, but for at least twenty-two centuries Albania and Greece belonged to the same state in various forms that it took.<ref>Abadzi, Helen. \"Historical Greek-Albanian Relations: Some Mysteries and Riddles.\" Mediterranean Quarterly 22, no. 1 (2011): 41\u201360.</ref> The ancient Greeks and Illyrian tribes that inhabited both countries were Indo-European tribes who intermarried with pre-Hellenic populations after arriving in the Balkans about four thousand years ago. Multiple migration events occurred then, as they have more recently, between both countries and peoples; with Greek colonies being established along the cost of Illyria, which corresponds to modern day coastal Albania.\n\nIn the Middle Ages, Albanian speakers such as the population group [[Arvanites]] migrated across Greece, establishing themselves throughout the country and playing a significant role in the [[Greek War for Independence]] and establishment of the modern Greek state.<ref>Bintliff, John. \"The ethnoarchaeology of a 'passive\u2019ethnicity: The Arvanites of Central Greece.\" The Usable Past. Greek Metahistories. Lanham-Boulder: Lexington Books (2003): 129\u201344.</ref> In addition, other Christian Albanians also took part in the Greek struggle against the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>Clair, William St. That Greece might still be free: the Philhellenes in the War of Independence. Open Book Publishers, 2008.</ref>\n\n{{further|Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus|Cham Albanians}}\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e \u0394. \u0391\u03b2\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 E. Panariti (8050603722).jpg|thumb|Foreign Minister of Albania [[Edmond Panariti]] and Foreign Minister of Greece [[Dimitris Avramopoulos]] in October 2012.]]\nAfter Albanian declaration of independence in 1912 land division between Albania and Greece was finally solved under the force of the Great Powers ([[Austria\u2013Hungary]] and [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]]) with the Florence Protocol. Relations did not improve until 1939 with the [[Italian invasion of Albania|occupation of Albania]] by [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]]. Greek and Albanian forces came into conflict during the [[Greco-Italian War]] even though during the [[Axis Occupation of Greece]] the Greek and Albanian resistance groups were in close contact and even exchanged information about the Nazi occupation forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahistoryofgreece.com/worldwarII.htm|title=Greece in the Second World War|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania]], being an ally of the [[Soviet Union]], was involved in the [[Greek Civil War]] (1946\u20131949) by supporting the communist led [[Greek Democratic Army]]. Leskovik, in southern Albania became for a period its headquarters. Several invasions were mounted from Albanian soil into the Greek region of Grammos. The communist guerrillas fled back to Albania once an operation was completed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shrader|first=Charles R.|title=The withered vine : logistics and the communist insurgency in Greece, 1945\u20131949|year=1999|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9780275965440|pages=188\u2013192|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Vu2i13Yq60QC&dq=gda+greek+civil+war|edition=[Online-Ausg.].}}</ref> Following a freeze lasting more than 30 years, the two countries re-established diplomatic relations in 1971, at an instance where economic cooperation and strategic calculations made [[Enver Hoxha]] and the right-wing [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]] explore paths of cooperation.<ref name=\"Nafpliotis2009\">{{cite book|author =Nafpliotis, Alexandros |title=Greece in the Balkans: Memory, Conflict and Exchange; \"The 1971 Re-establishment of Diplomatic Relations between Greece and Albania: Cooperation and Strategic Partnership within Cold War Bipolarity?\" in Anastasakis, Bechev and Vrousalis (eds.) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yH8fQAAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Newcastle: Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn= 9781443813150}}</ref>\n\n===Confederation aspirations===\nThere had been numerous discussions, research and attempts by Albanians and Greeks to form a confederation during the Ottoman period.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/3475296|title=Historical Greek-Albanian Relations: Some Mysteries and Riddles|first=Helen|last=Abadzi|date=Winter 2011|accessdate=27 June 2017|journal=Mediterranean Quarterly| volume=22|issue=1|pages=41\u201360|doi=10.1215/10474552-1189647}}</ref> In the 19th century there were plans to create a Greek-Albanian confederation, which was revived from the earlier 18th century plans. In 1907 a special protocol and memorandum of understanding was signed by [[Neoklis Kazazis]] and [[Ismail Qemali]], the first [[Prime Minister of Albania]]. Furthermore, Arvanite author Aristides Kollias in his book \"The proclamation of the Association of Arvanites\" states \"from 1881 to 1907 we have sustained efforts and repeated consultations between Greeks and Albanians to create a Greek-Albanian state.\" In addition, Thanos Paleologos-Anagnostopoulos in his book \"Greece and Albania in the early 20th century (1995)\" stated that Ismail Qemali, a philhellene, worked with numerous Greek politicians and lobbyists, including [[Arvanite]] leaders, on a possible Greek-Albanian federation, one that \"maintains national and religious independence of the two peoples.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.himara.gr/prosopa/974-ismail-kemal-filellinas|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03ae\u03bb \u039a\u03b5\u03bc\u03ac\u03bb, \u03bf \u03bc\u03ad\u03b3\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2|language=Greek|trans-title=Ismail Kemal, the great philhellene|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=27 June 2017|website=Himara.gr|publisher=Himara.gr}}</ref> Likewise, Neoklis Kazazis saw this as a way of Greece quashing Italian influence in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greeks-albanians.com/eng-m-ga/eng-m-ga-fed/126-efforts-for-the-creation-of-a-greek-albanian-federation-19th-20th-century|title=Efforts for the creation of a Greek-Albanian federation (19th\u201320th century)|first=Marios|last=Dimopoulos|accessdate=27 June 2017|website=Pelasgians-Greeks-Albanians}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Papandreou meets Greek minority representatives of Albania.jpg|thumb|Greek PM Papandreou meets [[Unity for Human Rights Party]] leader [[Vangjel Dule]] and [[Omonoia (organization)|Omonoia]] leader [[Vasil Bollano]].]]\nAfter the [[fall of communism]] in [[communism in Albania|Albania]] in 1992, a large number of [[economic refugee]]s and immigrants from Albania (and other formerly Communist countries including [[Bulgaria]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Romania]], [[Russia]], [[Ukraine]], [[Armenia]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) arrived in Greece, mostly as [[illegal immigrant]]s, to seek employment. [[Albanians in Greece]] comprise 60\u201365% of the total number of [[immigrants in Greece]]. According to the 2001 census, there are officially 443,550 holders of Albanian citizenship in Greece.<ref>[http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf Greencard1998_ ResPerm2004v4correctedFINAL.xls<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325222928/http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf|date=25 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albanians.gr|title=\u0397 \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Greece preferred and assisted [[Fatos Nano]] as Albanian leader due to him being Orthodox over Sali Berisha a Muslim, as Nano was seen as being friendlier to Greek interests.<ref name=\"Konidaris80\">{{cite book|last=Konidaris|first=Gerasimos|chapter=Examining policy responses to immigration in the light of interstate relations and foreign policy objectives: Greece and Albania|editor1-last=King|editor1-first=Russell|editor2-last=Schwandner-Sievers|editor2-first=Stephanie |title=The new Albanian migration|year=2005|location=Brighton|publisher=Sussex Academic|isbn=9781903900789|url=https://books.google.com/?id=05Mw4-b9oN0C|ref=harv}} pp. 80\u201381. \"Greece's favorite candidate in these elections was clearly MR. Nano. As emerges from the interview material, he \u2013unlike Berisha- was held in high esteem by the Greek side. It should not escape notice that Nano was by origin Orthodox Christian from Southern Albania, whereas Berisha was a northern Muslim... Greece's favour towards Nano was clearly demonstrated in June, when he was allowed to speak to a crowd of Albanian citizens at a pre-election rally in one of Athens' central squares. The police did not interfere and no arrests of illegal immigrants were made.\"</ref> During the [[Albanian Rebellion of 1997]], Greece participated in the multinational peacekeeping and humanitarian [[Operation Alba]]. Also, before the Operation Alba, Greece participated in the \"Operation Kosmas\" at 15 March 1997, which was the evacuation of 240 Foreign dignitaries from Albania. Today, both nations have described their relations as 'excellent' with Albania considering Greece one of its 'strongest and most important allies', as both are NATO member-states and are enjoying close relations nowadays.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\"/> Greece opposed for the route of the Trans Adriatic Pipeline passing through Albanian territory, as it would allow Albania to become transmission hub for gas in the Western Balkans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-prepares-to-play-role-in-the-region-gasification-03-30-2017|title=Albania Spies Gold in Projects Linked to TAP|date=31 March 2017|author=Mejdini, Fatjona|website=Balkan Insight}}</ref>\n\n==Modern relations==\n\nAfter the football game between [[Serbia v Albania (UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying)]], Albanian nationalists carrying flags and nationalist banners attacked [[Greeks in Albania|local ethnic Greeks]], attacked houses, smashed car windows.<ref name=balkaneu>[http://www.balkaneu.com/greek-ambassador-denounced-incident-place-minority-area-albania/ Greek ambassador denounced an incident taken place in a minority area in Albania] Independent Balkan News Agency.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Incidents in Serbia and abroad after stadium provocation|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/crimes.php?yyyy=2014&mm=10&dd=16&nav_id=91921|publisher=b92|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The incident triggered diplomatic intervention from Greece with the Greek foreign ministry sending a [[d\u00e9marche]] to the foreign ministry of Albania and demanded the trial of those responsible for the attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.protothema.gr/greek-demarche-to-albania-over-terrorism-of-greek-village|title=Greek Demarche to Albania over Terrorism of Greek Village|publisher=Proto Thema}}</ref> The Albanian foreign minister stated that \"quick and efficient reaction of the state police, identified the responsible people\".<ref name=balkaneu/>\n\nAccording to the [[Bank of Albania]], Greece continues to be the largest investor in Albania at 2017. The foreign direct investments made by Greece in Albania amounted to 1.22 billion euros in the first quarter of 2017, compared to 1.175 billion euros in 2016. Also, the interest of Greek companies to expand their activity in Albania is growing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/219808/article/ekathimerini/business/greece-remains-biggest-investor-in-albania|title=Greece remains biggest investor in Albania|date=4 July 2017|website=ekathimerini}}</ref>\n\nDuring massive wildfires, in August 2017, which have raged in Albania for weeks, Albanian authorities asked support from Greece. Greece sent two [[Canadair CL-415]] aircraft<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-08/03/c_136497634.htm|title=Albania turns to Greece, Italy for help with massive fires|date=3 August 2017|website=xinhuanet}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ata.gov.al/en/greece-sends-two-aircrafts-to-combat-fires-in-albania/|title=Greece sends two aircrafts &#91;sic&#93; to combat fires in Albania|date=3 August 2017|website=Albanian Telegraphic Agency}}</ref> and seven [[fire engines]] with their crew to assist Albania.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amna.gr/en/article/178820/%7B%7BngMeta.image%7D%7D|title=Greece sends six fire engines to Albania|date=13 August 2017|website=ANA-MPA}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 Albania earthquake]], Greece sent two earthquake expert \u0395\u039c\u0391\u039a (Special Units for Disaster Management) units consisting of 40 members, search and rescue dogs, a convoy of trucks<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/11/26/world/europe/ap-eu-albania-earthquake-the-latest.html The Latest: UN Sends Disaster Assessment Experts to Albania]</ref> and one C-130 airplane with food parcels.<ref name=dw>{{cite news| url=https://www.faxweb.al/termeti-i-fuqishem-ne-vend-greqia-nis-ndihma-per-vendin/|title =T\u00ebrmeti i fuqish\u00ebm n\u00eb vend, Greqia nis ndihma p\u00ebr vendin|language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://dosja.al/ministri-i-jashtem-i-greqise-shikon-nga-afer-demet-nga-termeti-keni-mbeshtetjen-tone/|title= Ministri i jasht\u00ebm i Greqis\u00eb shikon nga af\u00ebr d\u00ebmet nga t\u00ebrmeti: Keni mb\u00ebshtetjen ton\u00eb|language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://argjirolajm.net/lajm-i-mire-forcat-greke-shpetojne-jeten-e-nje-gruaje-nga-rrenojat-e-termetit-foto/|title =Lajm i mir\u00eb, forcat greke shp\u00ebtojn\u00eb jet\u00ebn e nj\u00eb gruaje nga rr\u00ebnojat e t\u00ebrmetit |language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Earthquake in Albania |url=https://www.msn.com/el-gr/news/world/%CF%83%CE%B5%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CF%8C%CF%82-%CF%83%CF%84%CE%B7%CE%BD-%CE%B1%CE%BB%CE%B2%CE%B1%CE%BD%CE%AF%CE%B1-%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%B1%CF%83%CF%8E%CF%83%CF%84%CE%B5%CF%82-%CF%84%CF%81%CE%AD%CF%87%CE%BF%CF%85%CE%BD-%CE%BD%CE%B1-%CF%83%CF%89%CE%B8%CE%BF%CF%8D%CE%BD-%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BD-%CE%B1%CE%AD%CF%81%CE%B1-%CE%BC%CE%B5%CF%84%CE%AC%CE%B4%CE%BF%CF%83%CE%B7%CF%82/ar-BBXqNKq?ocid=WidgetStore |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> In addition, the Greek Foreign Minister [[Nikos Dendias]] traveled to Tirana.<ref>[http://www.ekathimerini.com/246854/article/ekathimerini/news/greece-sending-help-to-albania-after-destructive-quake Greece sending help to Albania after destructive quake]</ref> Furthermore, Greek doctors and medicines were sent in order to help and support the civilians.<ref>[https://www.lifo.gr/now/world/260746/voitheia-stin-alvania-poioi-stelnoyn-giatroys-diasostes-kai-farmaka \u0392\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u2013 \u03a0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 ,\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c6\u03ac\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03b1]</ref> Moreover, the Greek army sent three [[Field kitchen|military mobile kitchens]] together with their personnel.<ref>[https://www.news.gr/kosmos/article/2058056/sismos-alvania-anthropistiki-voithia-apo-tin-ellada-me-kinita-magiria.html \u03a3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b2\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03bc\u03b1\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03af\u03b1]</ref> Also, a team of sixteen [[civil engineer]]s sent to Albania.<ref>[https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1538049/albania-eftase-i-16melis-omada-mixanikon-tis-ypiresias-antiseismikis-prostasias \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \u0388\u03c6\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u03b7 16\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b7\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a5\u03c0\u03b7\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2]</ref> The [[Hellenic Red Cross]] sent more than 200 tons of basic necessities.<ref>[https://www.newsbomb.gr/ellada/story/1034856/ees-xeperase-toys-200-tonoys-i-yliki-voitheia-gia-toys-pligentes-toy-seismoy-stin-alvania \u0395\u0395\u03a3: \u039e\u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 200 \u03c4\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b7 \u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b2\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03cd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1]</ref>\n\n===Greek minority of Albania===\nThe status of the Greek minority in Albania is one of the unresolved issues existing between both countries. The former communist regime had granted limited rights to the Greek minority within a specifically designated minority zone consisting 99 villages. Since the fall of communism, issues relating to the treatment of the Greek minority have frequently caused tension in relations between Greece and Albania. Current issues primarily involve respect for property rights, access to Greek language education outside the \"minority zone\", accurate census figures, and occasional violent incidents targeting the Greek minority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/265600.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307090122/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/265600.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 March 2017 |title=ALBANIA 2016 HUMAN RIGHTS REPORT |publisher=US Department of State |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://al.usembassy.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/140/2016/10/2012-Human-Rights-Report-Albania.pdf |title=ALBANIA 2012 HUMAN RIGHTS REPORT |publisher=US Embassy at Tirana |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://minorityrights.org/minorities/greeks/ |title=Minorities and indigenous peoples in Albania \u2013 Greeks|publisher=Minority Rights group |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/Albania/Albania-Greece-minority-properties-184104 |title=Albania-Greece: minority properties |publisher=OBC Transeuropa |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Albania's official position has been it that the Greek minority's rights are respected and further discussions on the matter can not be held until matters related to Greece's expelled former Cham Albanian minority are addressed{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}, while the position of the Greek government is that issues facing the Greek minority need to be resolved as a condition for Albania's accession to the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newpost.gr/politiki/5c1e38602837e2ed0648b89d/tsipras-se-alvania-sevasteite-ta-meionotika-dikaiomata-an-thelete-entaxi-stin-ee |title=Tsipras to Albania: \"Respect minority rights if you want EU membership\" (Original: \u03a4\u03c3\u03af\u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \"\u03a3\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1, \u03b1\u03bd \u03b8\u03ad\u03bb\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5 \u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u0395\") |publisher=NewPost.gr |date=22 December 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balkaneu.com/greek-turkish-relations-and-the-prespes-agreement-at-the-center-of-the-foreign-policy-council/ |title=Greek-Turkish relations and the Prespes Agreement at the center of the Foreign Policy Council |publisher=BalkanEU |date=21 December 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref>\nIn 1992, Greece proposed to Albania for a UN delegation to visit the minority areas and also Greece to establish a consulate in the region, both proposal were rejected by Albania.<ref>{{cite book| last = Bugajski | first = Janusz | title = Ethnic Politics in Eastern Europe: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KY0YDQAAQBAJ| publisher = Routledge|date=August 1995| isbn = 978-1563242830}}</ref>\n\n===Military cemeteries of fallen Greek soldiers===\nIn January 2018, following an agreement between the Greek and Albanian foreign ministers, a systematic effort to recover the bodies of fallen Greek soldiers from the [[Greco-Italian War]] was undertaken between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/225126/article/ekathimerini/news/mfa-welcomes-measures-to-disinter-identify-fallen-greek-soldiers-in-albaniaD|title=MFA welcomes measures to disinter, identify fallen Greek soldiers in Albania|website=ekathimerini}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"protothema\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.protothema.gr/world/article/753214/istoriki-stigmi-xekinise-i-ektafi-ton-ellinon-pesodon-tou-40-sto-metopo-tis-alvanias/ |title = \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03ae: \u039e\u03b5\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5 \u03b7 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03cc\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 '40 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|date = 22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.tribune.gr/greece/news/article/429714/429714.html |title = \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03cc\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b2\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|date = 21 January 2018}}</ref> It is estimated that between 6,800 and 8,000 fallen Greek soldiers were hastily buried on location following their death in battle and their remains not properly identified.<ref name=\"protothema\"/> Work by joint Greek-Albanian teams began on 22 January in the [[Kelcyre Gorge]], site of the [[Battle of Kleisoura Pass]]. A small number of [[Cham Albanians|Cham Albanian]] activists tried to disrupt the work but were removed by Albanian police.<ref name=\"protothema\"/> The remains of the Greek soldiers will be buried in the Greek military cemeteries in the [[Kelcyre Gorge]] and in the Greek minority village of [[Bularat]] (Vouliarates) near the Greek-Albanian border.<ref name=\"tribune\"/>\n\n===Cham issue===\n{{main|Cham issue}}\nThe ''Cham issue'' refers to a controversy which has been raised by [[Albania]] since the 1990s over the [[Right of Return|repatriation]] of the [[Cham Albanians]], who were [[Expulsion of Cham Albanians|expelled]] from the Greek region of [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] between 1944 and 1945, at the end of [[World War II]], citing the [[Axis-Cham Albanian collaboration|collaboration of the majority of them]] with the [[Axis Occupation of Greece|occupying forces]] of the [[Axis powers]].<ref>[[Albania\u2013Greece relations#Meyer|Meyer 2008]]: 705 \"The Albanian minority of the Chams collaborated in large parts with the Italians and the Germans\".</ref><ref name=\"RoudometofRobertson2001\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I9p_m7oXQ00C&pg=PA190|title=Nationalism, Globalization, and Orthodoxy: The Social Origins of Ethnic Conflict in the Balkans|author1=Victor Roudometof|author2=Roland Robertson|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2001|isbn=978-0-313-31949-5|pages=190\u2013}} \"During World War II, the majority of Chams sided with the Axis forces...\"</ref> While Albania presses for the issue to be re-opened, Greece considers the matter closed. However, it was agreed to create a bilateral commission, only about the property issue, as a technical problem. The commission was set up in 1999, but has not yet functioned.<ref name=\"Vickers, Miranda 2002\">{{cite book|title=The Albanians: A Modern History|last=Vickers|first=Miranda|date=2002|isbn=978-1780766959}}</ref>\n\n=== Kosovo Issue ===\nAlbania was the first state to recognize [[Kosovo]] as an independent state, meanwhile Greece [[Greece's reaction to the 2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|maintains a neutral position]] on the issue, stating that it would make a decision whether to recognise independent Kosovo or not after examining the issue in depth and that its decision would come as a result of close cooperation with European and neighboring countries, bearing in mind Serbia's role in maintaining regional stability.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/Articles/en-US/190208_alp_1300.htm Statements of FM Ms. Bakoyannis following the EU General Affairs and External Relations Council (GAERC, Brussels)], Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Greece, 18 February 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503235708/http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/Articles/en-US/190208_alp_1300.htm |date=3 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nAlbania maintains an [[embassy]] in [[Athens]] and [[consulate]]s in [[Ioannina]] and [[Thessaloniki]]. Greece maintains an embassy in [[Tirana]] and consulates in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]] and [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]].\n\n==Bilateral relations and cooperation==\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf \u03a4\u03b9\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03b5\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u039a\u03cc\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 (\u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2) (5509196312).jpg|thumb|left|140px|The two socialist leaders of Albania and Greece in 2011, [[Edi Rama]] and [[George Papandreou]]]]\nThe relations have significantly improved since 1991; Greece and Albania signed a Friendship, Cooperation, Good Neighborliness and Security Agreement on 21 March 1996.  Additionally, Greece is Albania's main foreign investor, having invested more than 400 million dollars in Albania, Albania's second largest trading partner, with Greek products accounting for some 21% of Albanian imports, and 12% of Albanian exports coming to Greece, and Albania's fourth largest donor country, having provided aid amounting to 73.8 million euros.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/en-US/Policy/Geographic+Regions/South-Eastern+Europe/Balkans/Bilateral+Relations/Albania/ Greek Ministry for Foreign Affairs: Bilateral relations between Greece and Albania].</ref>\n\nGreece is a staunch supporter of the Euro-Atlantic integration of the Republic of Albania, and since Albania's NATO entry in May 2009, Albanian-Greek relations have been developing on all fronts. The relations, particularly after the election victory of [[Edi Rama]] in 2013, have seen massive improvement and warming of relations between the two nations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greece.greekreporter.com/2013/11/04/karolos-papoulias-visits-albania/|title=Karolos Papoulias visits Albania|author =Maria Papathanasiou|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> for a short period of time, with the Albanian Chief of Foreign Policy, Ralf Gjoni, describing the diplomatic relations between two countries as \"excellent\". However, during the year 2014, only a year after Rama's election, Albania and Greece relations deteriorated and became increasingly strained, due to Rama's refusal of the agreement that defined the Maritime borders and set the Exclusive Economic Zone between the two countries, which Albania's previous government signed with Greece in 2009.<ref>[http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_07/08/2014_542016 Kathimerini Newspaper: Albania-Greece EEZ agreement to suffer setback, strain relations].</ref> Despite the difficulties in the relations between the two countries, Greece, is regarded as Albania's most important European Union ally and partner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.albeu.com/news/news/greece-support-eu-candidate-status-for-albania/150425/|title=Greece supports EU candidate status for Albania|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nBoth states are co-operating in many fields, such as political, judicial, energy and tourism. There are regular high-level visits between the two countries, and frequent contacts between the two countries' governments, parliaments and the local authorities on various matters concerning individual sectors and mutual interests. Big projects currently in running between the two countries include the touristic development of the Ionian coastline shared between the two countries, and the [[Trans Adriatic Pipeline|Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP)]]. Official meetings between the two governments and the parliaments are frequent and the armies of both states are conducting co-training in a regular basis as part of the NATO training programme for the modernization of the Albanian Army Forces.\n\nUnder the Greek EU Presidency, Albania, on 24 June 2014 was granted the official EU candidate status which coincides with the 10th anniversary of the \"Agenda 2014\" proposed by the Greek Government for boosting the integration of Albania and all the Western Balkan states into the European Union.\n\n==Notable visits==\n{{Expand section|date=February 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Guest\n! Host\n! Place of visit\n! Date of visit\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Foreign Minister of Greece|Foreign Minister]] [[Nikos Kotzias]]\n| {{flagicon|Albania}} [[Foreign Minister of Albania|Foreign Minister]] [[Ditmir Bushati]]\n| [[Tirana]], [[Albania]]\n| July 2015\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Albania}} [[Foreign Minister of Albania|Foreign Minister]] [[Ditmir Bushati]]\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Foreign Minister of Greece|Foreign Minister]] [[Nikos Kotzias]]\n| [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| May 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===State visit by Nikos Kotzias===\nIn July 2015, Greek Foreign Minister [[Nikos Kotzias]] visited Albania for two days (14\u201316) as part of his Western Balkans tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/greek-foreign-minister-announces-tour-visits-balkan-visit-albania|title=Greek Foreign Minister announces a tour of visits in the Balkan, he will also visit Albania|first=Edison|last=Kurani|date=25 May 2015|work=Independent Balkan News Agency|publisher=AM|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref> During his visit both nations reaffirmed their close ties, saying there are no open issues or taboo topics between the two. They agreed the sea issue will be sorted in due course, but both Ministers stressed the close, strategic and friendly ties of the people. Kotzias made note of the Greek National Minority, Albanians in Greece and their common past and future as bridges to sustainable, strong and fruitful relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/en/current-affairs/top-story/joint-statements-of-foreign-minister-kotzias-and-albanian-foreign-minister-ditmir-bushati-during-their-press-conference-tirana-15-july-2015.html|title=Joint statements of Foreign Minister Kotzias and Albanian Foreign Minister Ditmir Bushati during their press conference (Tirana, 15 July 2015)|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bilateral agreement on maritime borders==\nThe Greek Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis and the Albanian Prime Minister Sali Berisha signed the agreement in 2004 for the protection of their maritime borders allowing the two countries to further enhance their cooperation on the economic aspect. Following the agreement Kostas Karamanlis expressed his firm support for the integration of Albania in the European Union together with other Balkan countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.greekembassy.org/Embassy/content/en/Article.aspx?office=2&folder=1013&article=24712 |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041224013454/http://www.greekembassy.org/Embassy/Content/en/Article.aspx?office=2 |archive-date=24 December 2004 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Foreign relations of Albania]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Greece]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Franck, Debie. \"Greece, Italy and Europe in the Face of the Albanian Problem\". ''Geopolitics'' 5, no. 2 (2000): 186\u2013202\n*Roudometof, Victor [https://books.google.com/books?id=Xoww453NVQMC Collective memory, national identity, and ethnic conflict: Greece, Bulgaria and the Macedonian Question pp. 155\u2013164]\n*Xhudo, Gus. \"Tension Among Neighbours: Greek-Albanian Relations and their Impact on Regional Security and Stability\". ''Studies in Conflict and Terrorism'' 18 (1995):111\u2013143\n*Nafpliotis, Alexandros. \u201c[http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/europpblog/2013/09/25/greece-and-albania-would-both-benefit-substantially-from-closer-relations/ Greece and Albania would both benefit substantially from closer relations]\u201d. ''LSE EUROPP Blog'' 25 September 2013\n\n{{Foreign relations of Albania}}\n{{Hellenic foreign relations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albanian-Greek Relations}}\n[[Category:Albania\u2013Greece relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Albania|Greece]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Greece]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Albania and the Hellenic Republic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Albanian-Greek|Albania|Greece|filetype=svg}}\n{{see also|List of ambassadors of Albania to Greece}}\n\n'''Albanian\u2013Greek relations''' are the [[bilateral relations|bilateral]] [[diplomacy|foreign relations]] between [[Albania]] and [[Greece]]. Due to the presence of [[Albanian communities in Greece#Immigrants|Albanian immigrants in Greece]] and the [[Greeks in Albania|Greek minority in Albania]], historical and cultural ties<ref>Kondis, Basil. \"The Greek minority in Albania.\" Balkan studies 36, no. 1 (1995): 83\u2013102.</ref> as well as the frequent high-level contacts between the governments of Albania and Greece, the two countries today maintain strong, yet at times complicated, diplomatic relations.\n\nBoth countries are members of many international organizations, including the [[Council of Europe]] and [[NATO]], and share common political views about the Balkans and the world, with Greece being a strong supporter of the [[Accession of Albania to the European Union|EU candidacy]] of Albania, by proposing \"Agenda 2014\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Agenda 2014 |url=http://www.mfa.gr/images/docs/periferiaki_politiki/agenda_2014_en.pdf |publisher=mfa.gr |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> for promoting the [[Enlargement of the European Union|integration]] of all the [[Western Balkan]] states into the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Greece's EU Presidency and the Challenge of Western Balkan Enlargement Policies in Light of the Crisis |url=http://www.suedosteuropa.uni-graz.at/sites/default/files/publications/Panagiotou%20-%20Greece%20EU%20Presidency%20West%20Balkans%20-%20CSEES%20WPS.pdf |publisher=suedosteuropa.uni |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Under the [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Greek EU Presidency]], Albania was granted official EU candidate status on 24 June 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=EU candidate status for Albania|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-439_en.htm|publisher=[[European Commission]]|date=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=201delEU>{{Cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/albania/press_corner/all_news/news/2014/20140624_01_en.htm |title=European Union \u2013 EEAS (European External Action Service) &#124; EU candidate status for Albania |date=24 June 2013|publisher=European Union Delegation to Albania}}</ref> which coincided with the 10th anniversary of \"Agenda 2014\" proposed by the Greek Government as part of the 2004 EU-Western Balkans Summit in Thessaloniki.\n\nGreece is Albania's largest foreign investor and main trading partner.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://balkaneu.com/greece-is-the-biggest-investor-in-albania/ | title=Greece is the biggest investor in Albania| date=25 June 2018}}</ref> Along with Italy, Greece has strongly supported Albanian Euro-Atlantic integration such as Albania's entry to NATO in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mfa.gr/en/blog/greece-bilateral-relations/albania/ |title = Greece's Bilateral Relations}}</ref> Cooperation between the two governments and business sector exists in numerous fields such as market, energy, military, tourism and culture, with large bi-lateral projects such as the [[Trans Adriatic Pipeline]] and hydroelectric power plants being implemented. Greece has also been Albania's largest donors as well as the leading donor of the [[National Theater of Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Greece gives 2.5 mil. Euro to Albania for National Theater|url=http://albanians.gr/25-ek-euro-dini-i-elladha-stin-albania-gia-ethniko-theatro.html|publisher=albanians.gr|date=17 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nModern diplomatic relations between the two countries were established in 1971 and today are regarded as positive.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/enlargement/albanian-official-we-are-much-more-pro-european-several-eu-members-302813|title=Albanian official: 'We are much more pro-European than several EU members'|work=EurActiv.com|date=16 June 2014}}</ref> Despite the two peoples sharing common traditions, culture, history, and inter-ethnic relations diplomatic tensions relating to the Greek communities in Albania and Albanian communities in Greece continue to play a role in how both countries and people view one another.<ref>Hart, Laurie Kain. \"Culture, civilization, and demarcation at the northwest borders of Greece.\" American Ethnologist 26, no. 1 (1999): 196\u2013220.</ref> Current issues in diplomatic ties of the two NATO states include the abolition of the status of war that remains in effect between Greece and Albania, due to the Greek-Italian war in 1940<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-calls-on-greece-to-abolish-war-declaration|title=Albania Asks Greece to Declare War Finally Over|date=18 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/war-peace-albanian-grek-relations/|title=\"War\" and \"Peace\" in the Albanian-Greek relations|first=Edison|last=Kurani|work=Independent Balkan News Agency|publisher=AM|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-calls-on-greece-to-end-state-of-war|title=Albania Asks Greece to End State of War|date=14 October 2013}}</ref> and the human right issues the Greek minority faces in Albania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/summaries/s.albania952.html|title=Albania: The Greek Minority|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/1400/albania/greeks.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115070035/http://www.minorityrights.org/1400/albania/greeks.html |archivedate=15 November 2014  }}</ref> Despite some obstacles, and contrary to media portrayal, Albanians and Greeks continue to maintain intertwined relations in their respective countries, with a growing push by academics, cultural groups, NGO's, ethnic minorities, mixed families and other non-state actors to forge closer and stronger social and political ties.<ref>https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00400327/document</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://journals.openedition.org/balkanologie/2221 |title = Lines in the Family. Aspects of Family-Related Migration in Greek-Albanian Border|journal = Balkanologie. Revue d'\u00c9tudes Pluridisciplinaires|issue = Vol. XII, n\u00b0 2|date = 31 December 2010|last1 = Mantzos|first1 = Costas|last2 = Peglidou|first2 = Athena}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1007/978-3-319-13719-3_7|chapter = Albanian Immigrants in the Greek City: Spatial 'Invisibility' and Identity Management as a Strategy of Adaptation|title = Migration in the Southern Balkans|pages = 123\u2013142|series = IMISCOE Research Series|year = 2015|last1 = Kokkali|first1 = Ifigeneia|isbn = 978-3-319-13718-6}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nBoth countries and peoples claim autochthonous status in their respective countries and the wider Balkan region which has led to shared kinship as well as contested claims throughout history.\n\nAs a result of the close proximity of the two countries and peoples, European genetic research has shown a degree of genetic similarity between Albanians and Greeks, as well as other southern European populations such as southern Italians and Cypriots.<ref>Sokal, Robert R., Neal L. Oden, Pierre Legendre, Marie-Josee Fortin, Junhyong Kim, Barbara A. Thomson, Alain Vaudor, Rosalind M. Harding, and Guido Barbujani. \"Genetics and language in European populations.\" The American Naturalist 135, no. 2 (1990): 157\u2013175.</ref>\n\nSince the nineteenth century, both countries have been separate nation-states, but for at least twenty-two centuries Albania and Greece belonged to the same state in various forms that it took.<ref>Abadzi, Helen. \"Historical Greek-Albanian Relations: Some Mysteries and Riddles.\" Mediterranean Quarterly 22, no. 1 (2011): 41\u201360.</ref> The ancient Greeks and Illyrian tribes that inhabited both countries were Indo-European tribes who intermarried with pre-Hellenic populations after arriving in the Balkans about four thousand years ago. Multiple migration events occurred then, as they have more recently, between both countries and peoples; with Greek colonies being established along the cost of Illyria, which corresponds to modern day coastal Albania.\n\nIn the Middle Ages, Albanian speakers such as the population group [[Arvanites]] migrated across Greece, establishing themselves throughout the country and playing a significant role in the [[Greek War for Independence]] and establishment of the modern Greek state.<ref>Bintliff, John. \"The ethnoarchaeology of a 'passive\u2019ethnicity: The Arvanites of Central Greece.\" The Usable Past. Greek Metahistories. Lanham-Boulder: Lexington Books (2003): 129\u201344.</ref> In addition, other Christian Albanians also took part in the Greek struggle against the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>Clair, William St. That Greece might still be free: the Philhellenes in the War of Independence. Open Book Publishers, 2008.</ref>\n\n{{further|Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus|Cham Albanians}}\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e \u0394. \u0391\u03b2\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 E. Panariti (8050603722).jpg|thumb|Foreign Minister of Albania [[Edmond Panariti]] and Foreign Minister of Greece [[Dimitris Avramopoulos]] in October 2012.]]\nAfter Albanian declaration of independence in 1912 land division between Albania and Greece was finally solved under the force of the Great Powers ([[Austria\u2013Hungary]] and [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]]) with the Florence Protocol. Relations did not improve until 1939 with the [[Italian invasion of Albania|occupation of Albania]] by [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]]. Greek and Albanian forces came into conflict during the [[Greco-Italian War]] even though during the [[Axis Occupation of Greece]] the Greek and Albanian resistance groups were in close contact and even exchanged information about the Nazi occupation forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahistoryofgreece.com/worldwarII.htm|title=Greece in the Second World War|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania]], being an ally of the [[Soviet Union]], was involved in the [[Greek Civil War]] (1946\u20131949) by supporting the communist led [[Greek Democratic Army]]. Leskovik, in southern Albania became for a period its headquarters. Several invasions were mounted from Albanian soil into the Greek region of Grammos. The communist guerrillas fled back to Albania once an operation was completed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shrader|first=Charles R.|title=The withered vine : logistics and the communist insurgency in Greece, 1945\u20131949|year=1999|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9780275965440|pages=188\u2013192|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Vu2i13Yq60QC&dq=gda+greek+civil+war|edition=[Online-Ausg.].}}</ref> Following a freeze lasting more than 30 years, the two countries re-established diplomatic relations in 1971, at an instance where economic cooperation and strategic calculations made [[Enver Hoxha]] and the right-wing [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]] explore paths of cooperation.<ref name=\"Nafpliotis2009\">{{cite book|author =Nafpliotis, Alexandros |title=Greece in the Balkans: Memory, Conflict and Exchange; \"The 1971 Re-establishment of Diplomatic Relations between Greece and Albania: Cooperation and Strategic Partnership within Cold War Bipolarity?\" in Anastasakis, Bechev and Vrousalis (eds.) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yH8fQAAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Newcastle: Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn= 9781443813150}}</ref>\n\n===Confederation aspirations===\nThere had been numerous discussions, research and attempts by Albanians and Greeks to form a confederation during the Ottoman period.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/3475296|title=Historical Greek-Albanian Relations: Some Mysteries and Riddles|first=Helen|last=Abadzi|date=Winter 2011|accessdate=27 June 2017|journal=Mediterranean Quarterly| volume=22|issue=1|pages=41\u201360|doi=10.1215/10474552-1189647}}</ref> In the 19th century there were plans to create a Greek-Albanian confederation, which was revived from the earlier 18th century plans. In 1907 a special protocol and memorandum of understanding was signed by [[Neoklis Kazazis]] and [[Ismail Qemali]], the first [[Prime Minister of Albania]]. Furthermore, Arvanite author Aristides Kollias in his book \"The proclamation of the Association of Arvanites\" states \"from 1881 to 1907 we have sustained efforts and repeated consultations between Greeks and Albanians to create a Greek-Albanian state.\" In addition, Thanos Paleologos-Anagnostopoulos in his book \"Greece and Albania in the early 20th century (1995)\" stated that Ismail Qemali, a philhellene, worked with numerous Greek politicians and lobbyists, including [[Arvanite]] leaders, on a possible Greek-Albanian federation, one that \"maintains national and religious independence of the two peoples.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.himara.gr/prosopa/974-ismail-kemal-filellinas|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03ae\u03bb \u039a\u03b5\u03bc\u03ac\u03bb, \u03bf \u03bc\u03ad\u03b3\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2|language=Greek|trans-title=Ismail Kemal, the great philhellene|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=27 June 2017|website=Himara.gr|publisher=Himara.gr}}</ref> Likewise, Neoklis Kazazis saw this as a way of Greece quashing Italian influence in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greeks-albanians.com/eng-m-ga/eng-m-ga-fed/126-efforts-for-the-creation-of-a-greek-albanian-federation-19th-20th-century|title=Efforts for the creation of a Greek-Albanian federation (19th\u201320th century)|first=Marios|last=Dimopoulos|accessdate=27 June 2017|website=Pelasgians-Greeks-Albanians}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Papandreou meets Greek minority representatives of Albania.jpg|thumb|Greek PM Papandreou meets [[Unity for Human Rights Party]] leader [[Vangjel Dule]] and [[Omonoia (organization)|Omonoia]] leader [[Vasil Bollano]].]]\nAfter the [[fall of communism]] in [[communism in Albania|Albania]] in 1992, a large number of [[economic refugee]]s and immigrants from Albania (and other formerly Communist countries including [[Bulgaria]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Romania]], [[Russia]], [[Ukraine]], [[Armenia]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) arrived in Greece, mostly as [[illegal immigrant]]s, to seek employment. [[Albanians in Greece]] comprise 60\u201365% of the total number of [[immigrants in Greece]]. According to the 2001 census, there are officially 443,550 holders of Albanian citizenship in Greece.<ref>[http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf Greencard1998_ ResPerm2004v4correctedFINAL.xls<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325222928/http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf|date=25 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albanians.gr|title=\u0397 \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Greece preferred and assisted [[Fatos Nano]] as Albanian leader due to him being Orthodox over Sali Berisha a Muslim, as Nano was seen as being friendlier to Greek interests.<ref name=\"Konidaris80\">{{cite book|last=Konidaris|first=Gerasimos|chapter=Examining policy responses to immigration in the light of interstate relations and foreign policy objectives: Greece and Albania|editor1-last=King|editor1-first=Russell|editor2-last=Schwandner-Sievers|editor2-first=Stephanie |title=The new Albanian migration|year=2005|location=Brighton|publisher=Sussex Academic|isbn=9781903900789|url=https://books.google.com/?id=05Mw4-b9oN0C|ref=harv}} pp. 80\u201381. \"Greece's favorite candidate in these elections was clearly MR. Nano. As emerges from the interview material, he \u2013unlike Berisha- was held in high esteem by the Greek side. It should not escape notice that Nano was by origin Orthodox Christian from Southern Albania, whereas Berisha was a northern Muslim... Greece's favour towards Nano was clearly demonstrated in June, when he was allowed to speak to a crowd of Albanian citizens at a pre-election rally in one of Athens' central squares. The police did not interfere and no arrests of illegal immigrants were made.\"</ref> During the [[Albanian Rebellion of 1997]], Greece participated in the multinational peacekeeping and humanitarian [[Operation Alba]]. Also, before the Operation Alba, Greece participated in the \"Operation Kosmas\" at 15 March 1997, which was the evacuation of 240 Foreign dignitaries from Albania. Today, both nations have described their relations as 'excellent' with Albania considering Greece one of its 'strongest and most important allies', as both are NATO member-states and are enjoying close relations nowadays.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\"/> Greece opposed for the route of the Trans Adriatic Pipeline passing through Albanian territory, as it would allow Albania to become transmission hub for gas in the Western Balkans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/albania-prepares-to-play-role-in-the-region-gasification-03-30-2017|title=Albania Spies Gold in Projects Linked to TAP|date=31 March 2017|author=Mejdini, Fatjona|website=Balkan Insight}}</ref>\n\n==Modern relations==\n\nAfter the football game between [[Serbia v Albania (UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying)]], Albanian nationalists carrying flags and nationalist banners attacked [[Greeks in Albania|local ethnic Greeks]], attacked houses, smashed car windows.<ref name=balkaneu>[http://www.balkaneu.com/greek-ambassador-denounced-incident-place-minority-area-albania/ Greek ambassador denounced an incident taken place in a minority area in Albania] Independent Balkan News Agency.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Incidents in Serbia and abroad after stadium provocation|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/crimes.php?yyyy=2014&mm=10&dd=16&nav_id=91921|publisher=b92|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The incident triggered diplomatic intervention from Greece with the Greek foreign ministry sending a [[d\u00e9marche]] to the foreign ministry of Albania and demanded the trial of those responsible for the attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.protothema.gr/greek-demarche-to-albania-over-terrorism-of-greek-village|title=Greek Demarche to Albania over Terrorism of Greek Village|publisher=Proto Thema}}</ref> The Albanian foreign minister stated that \"quick and efficient reaction of the state police, identified the responsible people\".<ref name=balkaneu/>\n\nAccording to the [[Bank of Albania]], Greece continues to be the largest investor in Albania at 2017. The foreign direct investments made by Greece in Albania amounted to 1.22 billion euros in the first quarter of 2017, compared to 1.175 billion euros in 2016. Also, the interest of Greek companies to expand their activity in Albania is growing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/219808/article/ekathimerini/business/greece-remains-biggest-investor-in-albania|title=Greece remains biggest investor in Albania|date=4 July 2017|website=ekathimerini}}</ref>\n\nDuring massive wildfires, in August 2017, which have raged in Albania for weeks, Albanian authorities asked support from Greece. Greece sent two [[Canadair CL-415]] aircraft<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-08/03/c_136497634.htm|title=Albania turns to Greece, Italy for help with massive fires|date=3 August 2017|website=xinhuanet}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ata.gov.al/en/greece-sends-two-aircrafts-to-combat-fires-in-albania/|title=Greece sends two aircrafts &#91;sic&#93; to combat fires in Albania|date=3 August 2017|website=Albanian Telegraphic Agency}}</ref> and seven [[fire engines]] with their crew to assist Albania.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amna.gr/en/article/178820/%7B%7BngMeta.image%7D%7D|title=Greece sends six fire engines to Albania|date=13 August 2017|website=ANA-MPA}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 Albania earthquake]], Greece sent two earthquake expert \u0395\u039c\u0391\u039a (Special Units for Disaster Management) units consisting of 40 members, search and rescue dogs, a convoy of trucks<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/11/26/world/europe/ap-eu-albania-earthquake-the-latest.html The Latest: UN Sends Disaster Assessment Experts to Albania]</ref> and one C-130 airplane with food parcels.<ref name=dw>{{cite news| url=https://www.faxweb.al/termeti-i-fuqishem-ne-vend-greqia-nis-ndihma-per-vendin/|title =T\u00ebrmeti i fuqish\u00ebm n\u00eb vend, Greqia nis ndihma p\u00ebr vendin|language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://dosja.al/ministri-i-jashtem-i-greqise-shikon-nga-afer-demet-nga-termeti-keni-mbeshtetjen-tone/|title= Ministri i jasht\u00ebm i Greqis\u00eb shikon nga af\u00ebr d\u00ebmet nga t\u00ebrmeti: Keni mb\u00ebshtetjen ton\u00eb|language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://argjirolajm.net/lajm-i-mire-forcat-greke-shpetojne-jeten-e-nje-gruaje-nga-rrenojat-e-termetit-foto/|title =Lajm i mir\u00eb, forcat greke shp\u00ebtojn\u00eb jet\u00ebn e nj\u00eb gruaje nga rr\u00ebnojat e t\u00ebrmetit |language = sq}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Earthquake in Albania |url=https://www.msn.com/el-gr/news/world/%CF%83%CE%B5%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CF%8C%CF%82-%CF%83%CF%84%CE%B7%CE%BD-%CE%B1%CE%BB%CE%B2%CE%B1%CE%BD%CE%AF%CE%B1-%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%B1%CF%83%CF%8E%CF%83%CF%84%CE%B5%CF%82-%CF%84%CF%81%CE%AD%CF%87%CE%BF%CF%85%CE%BD-%CE%BD%CE%B1-%CF%83%CF%89%CE%B8%CE%BF%CF%8D%CE%BD-%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BD-%CE%B1%CE%AD%CF%81%CE%B1-%CE%BC%CE%B5%CF%84%CE%AC%CE%B4%CE%BF%CF%83%CE%B7%CF%82/ar-BBXqNKq?ocid=WidgetStore |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> In addition, the Greek Foreign Minister [[Nikos Dendias]] traveled to Tirana.<ref>[http://www.ekathimerini.com/246854/article/ekathimerini/news/greece-sending-help-to-albania-after-destructive-quake Greece sending help to Albania after destructive quake]</ref> Furthermore, Greek doctors and medicines were sent in order to help and support the civilians.<ref>[https://www.lifo.gr/now/world/260746/voitheia-stin-alvania-poioi-stelnoyn-giatroys-diasostes-kai-farmaka \u0392\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u2013 \u03a0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 ,\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c6\u03ac\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03b1]</ref> Moreover, the Greek army sent three [[Field kitchen|military mobile kitchens]] together with their personnel.<ref>[https://www.news.gr/kosmos/article/2058056/sismos-alvania-anthropistiki-voithia-apo-tin-ellada-me-kinita-magiria.html \u03a3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b2\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03bc\u03b1\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03af\u03b1]</ref> Also, a team of sixteen [[civil engineer]]s sent to Albania.<ref>[https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1538049/albania-eftase-i-16melis-omada-mixanikon-tis-ypiresias-antiseismikis-prostasias \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \u0388\u03c6\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u03b7 16\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b7\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a5\u03c0\u03b7\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2]</ref> The [[Hellenic Red Cross]] sent more than 200 tons of basic necessities.<ref>[https://www.newsbomb.gr/ellada/story/1034856/ees-xeperase-toys-200-tonoys-i-yliki-voitheia-gia-toys-pligentes-toy-seismoy-stin-alvania \u0395\u0395\u03a3: \u039e\u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 200 \u03c4\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b7 \u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b2\u03bf\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03cd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1]</ref>\n\n===Greek minority of Albania===\nThe status of the Greek minority in Albania is one of the unresolved issues existing between both countries. The former communist regime had granted limited rights to the Greek minority within a specifically designated minority zone consisting 99 villages. Since the fall of communism, issues relating to the treatment of the Greek minority have frequently caused tension in relations between Greece and Albania. Current issues primarily involve respect for property rights, access to Greek language education outside the \"minority zone\", accurate census figures, and occasional violent incidents targeting the Greek minority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/265600.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307090122/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/265600.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 March 2017 |title=ALBANIA 2016 HUMAN RIGHTS REPORT |publisher=US Department of State |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://al.usembassy.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/140/2016/10/2012-Human-Rights-Report-Albania.pdf |title=ALBANIA 2012 HUMAN RIGHTS REPORT |publisher=US Embassy at Tirana |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://minorityrights.org/minorities/greeks/ |title=Minorities and indigenous peoples in Albania \u2013 Greeks|publisher=Minority Rights group |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balcanicaucaso.org/eng/Areas/Albania/Albania-Greece-minority-properties-184104 |title=Albania-Greece: minority properties |publisher=OBC Transeuropa |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Albania's official position has been it that the Greek minority's rights are respected and further discussions on the matter can not be held until matters related to Greece's expelled former Cham Albanian minority are addressed{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}, while the position of the Greek government is that issues facing the Greek minority need to be resolved as a condition for Albania's accession to the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newpost.gr/politiki/5c1e38602837e2ed0648b89d/tsipras-se-alvania-sevasteite-ta-meionotika-dikaiomata-an-thelete-entaxi-stin-ee |title=Tsipras to Albania: \"Respect minority rights if you want EU membership\" (Original: \u03a4\u03c3\u03af\u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1: \"\u03a3\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1, \u03b1\u03bd \u03b8\u03ad\u03bb\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5 \u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u0395\") |publisher=NewPost.gr |date=22 December 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balkaneu.com/greek-turkish-relations-and-the-prespes-agreement-at-the-center-of-the-foreign-policy-council/ |title=Greek-Turkish relations and the Prespes Agreement at the center of the Foreign Policy Council |publisher=BalkanEU |date=21 December 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref>\nIn 1992, Greece proposed to Albania for a UN delegation to visit the minority areas and also Greece to establish a consulate in the region, both proposal were rejected by Albania.<ref>{{cite book| last = Bugajski | first = Janusz | title = Ethnic Politics in Eastern Europe: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KY0YDQAAQBAJ| publisher = Routledge|date=August 1995| isbn = 978-1563242830}}</ref>\n\n===Military cemeteries of fallen Greek soldiers===\nIn January 2018, following an agreement between the Greek and Albanian foreign ministers, a systematic effort to recover the bodies of fallen Greek soldiers from the [[Greco-Italian War]] was undertaken between the two countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/225126/article/ekathimerini/news/mfa-welcomes-measures-to-disinter-identify-fallen-greek-soldiers-in-albaniaD|title=MFA welcomes measures to disinter, identify fallen Greek soldiers in Albania|website=ekathimerini}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"protothema\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.protothema.gr/world/article/753214/istoriki-stigmi-xekinise-i-ektafi-ton-ellinon-pesodon-tou-40-sto-metopo-tis-alvanias/ |title = \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03ae: \u039e\u03b5\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5 \u03b7 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03cc\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 '40 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|date = 22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.tribune.gr/greece/news/article/429714/429714.html |title = \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03cc\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b2\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|date = 21 January 2018}}</ref> It is estimated that between 6,800 and 8,000 fallen Greek soldiers were hastily buried on location following their death in battle and their remains not properly identified.<ref name=\"protothema\"/> Work by joint Greek-Albanian teams began on 22 January in the [[Kelcyre Gorge]], site of the [[Battle of Kleisoura Pass]]. A small number of [[Cham Albanians|Cham Albanian]] activists tried to disrupt the work but were removed by Albanian police.<ref name=\"protothema\"/> The remains of the Greek soldiers will be buried in the Greek military cemeteries in the [[Kelcyre Gorge]] and in the Greek minority village of [[Bularat]] (Vouliarates) near the Greek-Albanian border.<ref name=\"tribune\"/>\n\n===Cham issue===\n{{main|Cham issue}}\nThe ''Cham issue'' refers to a controversy which has been raised by [[Albania]] since the 1990s over the [[Right of Return|repatriation]] of the [[Cham Albanians]], who were [[Expulsion of Cham Albanians|expelled]] from the Greek region of [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] between 1944 and 1945, at the end of [[World War II]], citing the [[Axis-Cham Albanian collaboration|collaboration of the majority of them]] with the [[Axis Occupation of Greece|occupying forces]] of the [[Axis powers]].<ref>[[Albania\u2013Greece relations#Meyer|Meyer 2008]]: 705 \"The Albanian minority of the Chams collaborated in large parts with the Italians and the Germans\".</ref><ref name=\"RoudometofRobertson2001\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I9p_m7oXQ00C&pg=PA190|title=Nationalism, Globalization, and Orthodoxy: The Social Origins of Ethnic Conflict in the Balkans|author1=Victor Roudometof|author2=Roland Robertson|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2001|isbn=978-0-313-31949-5|pages=190\u2013}} \"During World War II, the majority of Chams sided with the Axis forces...\"</ref> While Albania presses for the issue to be re-opened, Greece considers the matter closed. However, it was agreed to create a bilateral commission, only about the property issue, as a technical problem. The commission was set up in 1999, but has not yet functioned.<ref name=\"Vickers, Miranda 2002\">{{cite book|title=The Albanians: A Modern History|last=Vickers|first=Miranda|date=2002|isbn=978-1780766959}}</ref>\n\n=== Kosovo Issue ===\nAlbania was the first state to recognize [[Kosovo]] as an independent state, meanwhile Greece [[Greece's reaction to the 2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|maintains a neutral position]] on the issue, stating that it would make a decision whether to recognise independent Kosovo or not after examining the issue in depth and that its decision would come as a result of close cooperation with European and neighboring countries, bearing in mind Serbia's role in maintaining regional stability.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/Articles/en-US/190208_alp_1300.htm Statements of FM Ms. Bakoyannis following the EU General Affairs and External Relations Council (GAERC, Brussels)], Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Greece, 18 February 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503235708/http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/Articles/en-US/190208_alp_1300.htm |date=3 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nAlbania maintains an [[embassy]] in [[Athens]] and [[consulate]]s in [[Ioannina]] and [[Thessaloniki]]. Greece maintains an embassy in [[Tirana]] and consulates in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]] and [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]].\n\n==Bilateral relations and cooperation==\n[[File:Edi Rama with George Papandreou.jpg|thumb|left|140px|The two socialist leaders of Albania and Greece in 2011, [[Edi Rama]] and [[George Papandreou]]]]\nThe relations have significantly improved since 1991; Greece and Albania signed a Friendship, Cooperation, Good Neighborliness and Security Agreement on 21 March 1996.  Additionally, Greece is Albania's main foreign investor, having invested more than 400 million dollars in Albania, Albania's second largest trading partner, with Greek products accounting for some 21% of Albanian imports, and 12% of Albanian exports coming to Greece, and Albania's fourth largest donor country, having provided aid amounting to 73.8 million euros.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/en-US/Policy/Geographic+Regions/South-Eastern+Europe/Balkans/Bilateral+Relations/Albania/ Greek Ministry for Foreign Affairs: Bilateral relations between Greece and Albania].</ref>\n\nGreece is a staunch supporter of the Euro-Atlantic integration of the Republic of Albania, and since Albania's NATO entry in May 2009, Albanian-Greek relations have been developing on all fronts. The relations, particularly after the election victory of [[Edi Rama]] in 2013, have seen massive improvement and warming of relations between the two nations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greece.greekreporter.com/2013/11/04/karolos-papoulias-visits-albania/|title=Karolos Papoulias visits Albania|author =Maria Papathanasiou|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> for a short period of time, with the Albanian Chief of Foreign Policy, Ralf Gjoni, describing the diplomatic relations between two countries as \"excellent\". However, during the year 2014, only a year after Rama's election, Albania and Greece relations deteriorated and became increasingly strained, due to Rama's refusal of the agreement that defined the Maritime borders and set the Exclusive Economic Zone between the two countries, which Albania's previous government signed with Greece in 2009.<ref>[http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_07/08/2014_542016 Kathimerini Newspaper: Albania-Greece EEZ agreement to suffer setback, strain relations].</ref> Despite the difficulties in the relations between the two countries, Greece, is regarded as Albania's most important European Union ally and partner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.albeu.com/news/news/greece-support-eu-candidate-status-for-albania/150425/|title=Greece supports EU candidate status for Albania|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nBoth states are co-operating in many fields, such as political, judicial, energy and tourism. There are regular high-level visits between the two countries, and frequent contacts between the two countries' governments, parliaments and the local authorities on various matters concerning individual sectors and mutual interests. Big projects currently in running between the two countries include the touristic development of the Ionian coastline shared between the two countries, and the [[Trans Adriatic Pipeline|Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP)]]. Official meetings between the two governments and the parliaments are frequent and the armies of both states are conducting co-training in a regular basis as part of the NATO training programme for the modernization of the Albanian Army Forces.\n\nUnder the Greek EU Presidency, Albania, on 24 June 2014 was granted the official EU candidate status which coincides with the 10th anniversary of the \"Agenda 2014\" proposed by the Greek Government for boosting the integration of Albania and all the Western Balkan states into the European Union.\n\n==Notable visits==\n{{Expand section|date=February 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Guest\n! Host\n! Place of visit\n! Date of visit\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Foreign Minister of Greece|Foreign Minister]] [[Nikos Kotzias]]\n| {{flagicon|Albania}} [[Foreign Minister of Albania|Foreign Minister]] [[Ditmir Bushati]]\n| [[Tirana]], [[Albania]]\n| July 2015\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Albania}} [[Foreign Minister of Albania|Foreign Minister]] [[Ditmir Bushati]]\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Foreign Minister of Greece|Foreign Minister]] [[Nikos Kotzias]]\n| [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| May 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===State visit by Nikos Kotzias===\nIn July 2015, Greek Foreign Minister [[Nikos Kotzias]] visited Albania for two days (14\u201316) as part of his Western Balkans tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/greek-foreign-minister-announces-tour-visits-balkan-visit-albania|title=Greek Foreign Minister announces a tour of visits in the Balkan, he will also visit Albania|first=Edison|last=Kurani|date=25 May 2015|work=Independent Balkan News Agency|publisher=AM|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref> During his visit both nations reaffirmed their close ties, saying there are no open issues or taboo topics between the two. They agreed the sea issue will be sorted in due course, but both Ministers stressed the close, strategic and friendly ties of the people. Kotzias made note of the Greek National Minority, Albanians in Greece and their common past and future as bridges to sustainable, strong and fruitful relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/en/current-affairs/top-story/joint-statements-of-foreign-minister-kotzias-and-albanian-foreign-minister-ditmir-bushati-during-their-press-conference-tirana-15-july-2015.html|title=Joint statements of Foreign Minister Kotzias and Albanian Foreign Minister Ditmir Bushati during their press conference (Tirana, 15 July 2015)|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bilateral agreement on maritime borders==\nThe Greek Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis and the Albanian Prime Minister Sali Berisha signed the agreement in 2004 for the protection of their maritime borders allowing the two countries to further enhance their cooperation on the economic aspect. Following the agreement Kostas Karamanlis expressed his firm support for the integration of Albania in the European Union together with other Balkan countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.greekembassy.org/Embassy/content/en/Article.aspx?office=2&folder=1013&article=24712 |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041224013454/http://www.greekembassy.org/Embassy/Content/en/Article.aspx?office=2 |archive-date=24 December 2004 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Foreign relations of Albania]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Greece]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Franck, Debie. \"Greece, Italy and Europe in the Face of the Albanian Problem\". ''Geopolitics'' 5, no. 2 (2000): 186\u2013202\n*Roudometof, Victor [https://books.google.com/books?id=Xoww453NVQMC Collective memory, national identity, and ethnic conflict: Greece, Bulgaria and the Macedonian Question pp. 155\u2013164]\n*Xhudo, Gus. \"Tension Among Neighbours: Greek-Albanian Relations and their Impact on Regional Security and Stability\". ''Studies in Conflict and Terrorism'' 18 (1995):111\u2013143\n*Nafpliotis, Alexandros. \u201c[http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/europpblog/2013/09/25/greece-and-albania-would-both-benefit-substantially-from-closer-relations/ Greece and Albania would both benefit substantially from closer relations]\u201d. ''LSE EUROPP Blog'' 25 September 2013\n\n{{Foreign relations of Albania}}\n{{Hellenic foreign relations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albanian-Greek Relations}}\n[[Category:Albania\u2013Greece relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Albania|Greece]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Greece]]\n", "name_user": "T\u00farelio", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)Duplicate:File:Edi Rama with George Papandreou.jpg\u2192File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf \u03a4\u03b9\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03b5\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u039a\u03cc\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 (\u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2) (5509196312).jpgExact or scaled-down duplicate:c::File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u